005), National lightweight double sculls champion. \n*[[Kelly Salchow]], former Olympic rower (2004 and 2008 Olympic Games), Women's Quadruple Sculls\n*[[Kenny Satterfield]], professional basketball player, 2001\u201312\n*[[Kerry Schall]], competed on reality show ''[[The Ultimate Fighter 2]]'', professional [[Mixed martial arts|MMA]] fighter<ref>http://www.gregwapling.com/tv/the-ultimate-fighter/the-ultimate-fighter-biographies.html</ref>\n*[[Lance Stephenson]], basketball player for [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n*[[Andrew Stewart (gridiron football)|Andrew Stewart]], football player\n*[[Clint Stickdorn]], football player\n*[[Tom Thacker (basketball)|Tom Thacker]], basketball player, NCAA and NBA champion, top pick of [[1963 NBA draft]]\n*[[Tony Trabert]], tennis player, Wimbledon and U.S. Open champion, [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Jack Twyman]], basketball player, [[College Basketball Hall of Fame]], 6-time NBA All-Star\n*[[Nick Van Exel]], basketball player, 1998 NBA All-Star\n*[[LaDaris Vann]], football player\n*[[Roland West (basketball)|Roland West]], basketball player\n*[[Jim Herman]], professional golfer, who plays on the PGA tour, 3 professional wins.\n\n[[File:KevinYouklis.jpg|thumb|right|160px|[[Kevin Youkilis]]]]\n*[[Kevin Youkilis]], 3-time All-Star, Gold Glove winner, 2-time World Series champion, [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] player 2004-13\n*[[Curtis Young]], NFL defensive end, Green Bay Packers\n*[[James White (basketball)|James White]], NBA guard/forward for [[New York Knicks]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/w/whiteja02.html|title= James White\n|publisher= Basketball-Reference.Com  |accessdate= November 15, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Bob Wiesenhahn]], basketball player, 1961 NCAA champion with [[Cincinnati Bearcats]], 11th overall pick of [[1961 NBA draft]]\n*[[David J. Williams]], Director of Architecture, Musician\n*[[John Williamson (basketball, born 1986)|John Williamson]] (born 1986), basketball player for [[Hapoel Tel Aviv B.C.]] of the [[Israeli Basketball Premier League]]<ref>[http://www.gobearcats.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/john_williamson_262298.html]</ref> \n*[[Eric Wilson (linebacker, born 1994)|Eric Wilson]], [[American football|football]] player\n*[[Mary Wineberg]], 2008 Olympic gold medalist, 4 \u00d7 400 m relay\n*[[Derek Wolfe]], NFL defensive end, [[Denver Broncos]]\n*[[D. J. Woods]], [[Canadian Football League]] wide receiver, [[Ottawa Redblacks]]\n*[[Mike Woods (American football)|Mike Woods]], All-American and NFL player\n*[[Tony Yates]], basketball player for two-time national champion [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati Bearcats]], head coach 1983-89\n\n==Notable faculty==\n\n*[[Neil Armstrong]] (until death), astronaut, professor of aerospace engineering\n*[[Carl Blegen]], first scientific explorer of [[Troy]]\n* [[Karen L. Gould]] (born 1948), President of [[Brooklyn College]]\n*[[Michael Griffith (novelist)|Michael Griffith]], author\n*[[Neil Rackham]], author of ''Spin Selling''\n*[[George Rieveschl]], inventor of [[diphenhydramine]] ([[Benadryl]])\n*[[Albert Sabin]], developed the oral live [[polio vaccine]]\n*[[Vernon L. Scarborough]], [[Mesoamerican]] archaeologist, professor, and anthropology department head\n*[[Herman Schnieder]], father of [[co-operative education]]\n*[[Donald Shell]], inventor of [[Shell sort]]\n*[[Amy Townsend-Small]], Director of the Environmental Studies Program<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsci.uc.edu/departments/geology/faculty--staff-and-students.html?eid=townseay|title=Faculty, Staff and Students|website=University of Cincinnati|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n*[[Carol Tyler]], cartoonist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n*[http://www.magazine.uc.edu/exclusives/famousalumni.htm UC Magazine on Famous Alumni]\n\n{{University of Cincinnati |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati people|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by university or college in Ohio|University of Cincinnati people]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati-related lists|University of Cincinnati]]\n", "name_user": "DeltaQuad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Hammad Siddiqiclosed as soft delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_University_of_Cincinnati_people"}
{"title_page": "Qonqurtai", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Qonqurtai|spouse-type=|regent=|queen=|religion=|mother=Ajuja|father=[[Hulagu Khan]]|house-type=Dynasty|house=[[Borjigin]]|issue=|death_place=[[Karabakh]], [[Ilkhanate]]|image=|death_date=18 January 1284|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|birth_date=|successor=|predecessor=|reign=1277 - 1282 <br> 12 July 1282 - 18 January 1284|succession=Viceroy of [[Anatolia]]|caption=|reg-type=}}'''cQonqurtai''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0642\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0649}}) was a Mongol prince and viceroy of [[Anatolia]] for the [[Ilkhanate]] [[khanate]].\n\n== Life ==\nQonqurtai was born to [[Hulagu Khan]] and Ajuja Aguchi, his [[Khitan people|Khitan]] [[Concubinage|concubine]] wife. Qonqurtai was Hulagu's ninth son and was the senior commander during the reign of his brother [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]]. He was twice appointed as viceroy of Anatolia, first during the reign of Abaqa and then under [[Tekuder]]. His winter quarters were in [[:tr: Kazova|Kazova]] plains near [[Tokat]], while his viceroyalty itself has centred around [[Kayseri]].\n\n== Rule in Anatolia ==\nQonqurtai was appointed as commander of Ilkhanid army in Anatolia with [[Shams al-Din Juvayni]] as his vizier after the [[Battle of Elbistan]] in 1277 to support the [[Sultanate of Rum]] against revolting [[Turkmens|Turcomans]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lane, George, 1952-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/890796255|title=Early Mongol rule in thirteenth-century Iran : a Persian renaissance|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-134-43103-8|location=London|pages=201|oclc=890796255}}</ref> He pursed [[Jimri]], a claimant to Seljuk throne, and attacked his patrons - the [[Karamanids]]. As a consequence, [[Mehmet I of Karaman]] was captured and executed together with his sons Mahmud and Karaman in October 1277.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/219570995|title=The Cambridge history of Turkey|publisher=|others=Fleet, Kate., Faroqhi, Suraiya, 1941-, Kasaba, Re\u015fat, 1954-|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62093-2|location=New York|pages=70|oclc=219570995}}</ref>  Qonqurtai further authorised [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] to act on his behalf. He aided [[Kaykhusraw III]]'s efforts to subdue Karamanids and [[Eshrefids]] in 1282. However,  Qonqurtai had to cease his activities upon hearing the death of Abaqa.\n\nUpon the death of [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]],  Qonqurtai supported [[Tekuder]]'s succession in [[Maragheh|Maragha]], who in return gave him the hand of Toqiyatai Khatun, a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282. He was also re-appointed as viceroy of Anatolia the same day.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjZYDwAAQBAJ|title=Women in Mongol Iran: The Khatuns, 1206-1335|date=2017-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-1-4744-1549-1|language=en}}</ref> However, later in Tekuder's reign, he shifted his alliance to [[Arghun]], which made the former suspicious. Qonqurtai was summoned to Karabakh, accused of conspiracy and was arrested by Teg\u00fcder's son-in-law, Alinaq - the viceroy of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] on 17 January 1284, and was executed next day by breaking his neck.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RgpRDAAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols' Middle East: Continuity and Transformation in Ilkhanid Iran|last2=Melville|first2=Charles|date=2016-06-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-31472-6|location=|pages=113|language=en}}</ref> Later, Arghun had put Tekuder on trial for Qonqurtai's death, who suffered the same penalty as him.\n\n== Personality ==\nHe was described as a wise ruler in ''[[Zafarnamah (Mustawfi)|Zafarnamah]]'' by [[Hamdallah Mustawfi|Hamdullah Mustawfi]],<ref name=\":0\">L. J. Ward, \u201cThe \u1e92afar-n\u0101mah of \u1e24amd All\u0101h Mustaufi and the Il-Kh\u0101n dynasty of Iran,\u201d Ph.D. diss, p.204, University of Manchester, 1983.</ref> while [[Al-Mansur Qalawun|Qalawun]] considered him as a not only dishonorable, but also cruel man.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allouche|first=Adel|date=1990|title=Teg\u00fcder's Ultimatum to Qalawun|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0020743800034358/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Middle East Studies|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=437\u2013446|doi=10.1017/S0020743800034358|issn=0020-7438|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nHe was married to Toqiyatai Khatun (d. 1292), a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282, and only two of his children reached adulthood.<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\n# Esen Timur Kharbanda (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/133445|title=Mediating Sacred Kingship: Conversion and Sovereignty in Mongol Iran|website=deepblue.lib.umich.edu|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>)\n## Pulad\n# Ildar (executed by [[Ghazan]] in 1296<ref name=\":1\" />)\n## Aq Timur\n# Karai (died in infancy)\n# Changtimur (died in infancy)\n# Tashtimur (died in infancy)\n# Ashightimur (died in infancy)\n# Akash m (died in infancy)\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1284 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ilkhanate]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire people]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Qonqurtai|spouse-type=|regent=|queen=|religion=|mother=Ajuja|father=[[Hulagu Khan]]|house-type=Dynasty|house=[[Borjigin]]|issue=|death_place=[[Karabakh]], [[Ilkhanate]]|image=|death_date=18 January 1284|birth_place=[[Mongolia]]|birth_date=|successor=|predecessor=|reign=1277 - 1282 <br> 12 July 1282 - 18 January 1284|succession=Viceroy of [[Anatolia]]|caption=|reg-type=}}'''cQonqurtai''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0642\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0627\u0649}}) was a Mongol prince and viceroy of [[Anatolia]] for the [[Ilkhanate]] [[khanate]].\n\n== Life ==\nQonqurtai was born to [[Hulagu Khan]] and Ajuja Aguchi, his [[Khitan people|Khitan]] [[Concubinage|concubine]] wife. Qonqurtai was Hulagu's ninth son and was the senior commander during the reign of his brother [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]]. He was twice appointed as viceroy of Anatolia, first during the reign of Abaqa and then under [[Tekuder]]. His winter quarters were in [[:tr: Kazova|Kazova]] plains near [[Tokat]], while his viceroyalty itself has centred around [[Kayseri]].\n\n== Rule in Anatolia ==\nHe was appointed as commander of Ilkhanid army in Anatolia with [[Shams al-Din Juvayni]] as his vizier after the [[Battle of Elbistan]] in 1277 to support the [[Sultanate of Rum]] against revolting [[Turkmens|Turcomans]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lane, George, 1952-|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/890796255|title=Early Mongol rule in thirteenth-century Iran : a Persian renaissance|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-134-43103-8|location=London|pages=201|oclc=890796255}}</ref> He pursed [[Jimri]], a claimant to Seljuk throne, and attacked his patrons - the [[Karamanids]]. As a consequence, [[Mehmet I of Karaman]] was captured and executed together with his sons Mahmud and Karaman in October 1277.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/219570995|title=The Cambridge history of Turkey|publisher=|others=Fleet, Kate., Faroqhi, Suraiya, 1941-, Kasaba, Re\u015fat, 1954-|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62093-2|location=New York|pages=70|oclc=219570995}}</ref> He further authorised [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] to act on his behalf. He aided [[Kaykhusraw III]]'s efforts to subdue Karamanids and [[Eshrefids]] in 1282. However, he had to cease his activities upon hearing the death of Abaqa.\n\nUpon the death of [[Abaqa Khan|Abaqa]], he supported [[Tekuder]]'s succession in [[Maragheh|Maragha]], who in return gave him the hand of Toqiyatai Khatun, a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282. He was also re-appointed as viceroy of Anatolia the same day.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjZYDwAAQBAJ|title=Women in Mongol Iran: The Khatuns, 1206-1335|date=2017-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-1-4744-1549-1|language=en}}</ref> However, later in Tekuder's reign, he shifted his alliance to [[Arghun]], which made the former suspicious. Qonqurtai was summoned to Karabakh, accused of conspiracy and was arrested by Teg\u00fcder's son-in-law, Alinaq - the viceroy of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] on 17 January 1284, and was executed next day by breaking his neck.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicola|first=Bruno De|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RgpRDAAAQBAJ|title=The Mongols' Middle East: Continuity and Transformation in Ilkhanid Iran|last2=Melville|first2=Charles|date=2016-06-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-31472-6|location=|pages=113|language=en}}</ref> Later, Arghun had put Tekuder on trial for Qonqurtai's death, who suffered the same penalty as him.\n\n== Personality ==\nHe was described as a wise ruler in ''[[Zafarnamah (Mustawfi)|Zafarnamah]]'' by [[Hamdallah Mustawfi|Hamdullah Mustawfi]],<ref name=\":0\">L. J. Ward, \u201cThe \u1e92afar-n\u0101mah of \u1e24amd All\u0101h Mustaufi and the Il-Kh\u0101n dynasty of Iran,\u201d Ph.D. diss, p.204, University of Manchester, 1983.</ref> while [[Al-Mansur Qalawun|Qalawun]] considered him as a not only dishonorable, but also cruel man.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Allouche|first=Adel|date=1990|title=Teg\u00fcder's Ultimatum to Qalawun|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/product/identifier/S0020743800034358/type/journal_article|journal=International Journal of Middle East Studies|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=437\u2013446|doi=10.1017/S0020743800034358|issn=0020-7438|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nHe was married to Toqiyatai Khatun (d. 1292), a [[Keraites|Keraite]] concubine of Hulagu and niece of [[Doquz Khatun|Dokuz Khatun]] on 12 July 1282, and only two of his children reached adulthood.<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\