 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Talal Asad]] \u2013 Professor of Anthropology and Religious Studies at [[City University of New York|CUNY]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.gc.cuny.edu/anthropology/fac_asad.html|title=Profile Talal Asad |publisher=City University of New York |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n*[[Farooq Azam]] \u2013 Distinguished Professor at [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], [[UCSD]]; researcher in the field of marine microbiology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sio.ucsd.edu/Profile/fazam |title=:: Scripps Institution Of Oceanography, Ucsd  |publisher=Sio.ucsd.edu |date=January 8, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Ayesha Jalal]] \u2013 [[MacArthur Fellow]] and Richardson Professor of History at [[Tufts University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fletcher.tufts.edu/faculty/jalal/default.shtml |title=The Fletcher School \u2013 Faculty |publisher=Fletcher.tufts.edu |date=August 22, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120151225/http://fletcher.tufts.edu/faculty/jalal/default.shtml |archivedate=November 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n*[[Mohammad Aslam Khan Khalil]] \u2013 Professor of Physics at [[Portland State University]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.directory.pdx.edu/index.php?getinfo=1&uid=aslamk&preferredcn_e= |title=Portland State University &#124; Directory |publisher=Directory.pdx.edu |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612103444/http://www.directory.pdx.edu/index.php?getinfo=1&uid=aslamk&preferredcn_e= |archivedate=June 12, 2010 }}</ref> a highly cited researcher in the field of [[atmospheric physics]]\n*[[Sadaf Jaffer]] \u2013 the first female Muslim American mayor, first female [[South Asian]] mayor, and first female [[Pakistani-American]] mayor in the United States, of [[Montgomery, New Jersey|Montgomery]] in [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset County]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/news/2019/05/first-female-muslim-mayor-in-the-us-calls-this-nj-town-home.html|title=First female Muslim mayor in the U.S. calls this N.J. town home|author=Olivia Rizzo|publisher=New Jersey On-Line LLC|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019|quote=She is now the first female South Asian mayor of a New Jersey municipality and the first female Muslim mayor in the state. She is also believed to be the first female Muslim mayor, female Pakistani-American mayor and first female South Asian-American mayor first in the nation, according to Religionnews.com.}}</ref>\n*[[Hafeez Malik]]  \u2013  Professor of Political Science at [[Villanova University]], in [[Pennsylvania]]<ref name=\"Hafeez Malik Villanova University profile\">[http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/Politics/ComparativePolitics/IndiaPakistan/?view=usa&ci=9780195475234 Hafeez Malik], May 22, 2010.</ref>\n* [[Nergis Mavalvala]], Kathleen Marble Professor of Astrophysics at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), and 2010 [[MacArthur Fellow]]; part of the team that made the [[Gravitational wave observation|first direct gravitational wave observation]]\n*[[Zia Mian]] \u2013 [[physicist]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Princeton University |url=http://www.princeton.edu/sgs/faculty-staff/zia-mian/ |title=Zia Mian |publisher=Princeton.edu |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wws.princeton.edu/people/display_person.xml?netid=zia&all=yes |title=Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs &#124; Display Person |publisher=Wws.princeton.edu |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622195722/https://wws.princeton.edu/people/display_person.xml?netid=zia&all=yes |archivedate=June 22, 2010 }}</ref><ref>http://www.isodarco.it/courses/andalo06/paper/andalo06_mian_abstract-CV.pdf</ref>\n*[[Adil Najam]] \u2013 Professor of Geography and International Relations and Director of the Pardee Center at [[Boston University]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iisd.org/about/staffbio.aspx?id=569 |title=Adil Najam biography |publisher=Iisd.org |date=February 14, 2006 |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709213513/http://www.iisd.org/about/staffbio.aspx?id=569 |archivedate=July 9, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> founding editor of popular blog [[Pakistaniat]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistaniat.com/about/ |title=About Atp : All Things Pakistan |publisher=Pakistaniat.com |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>\n* S. [[Hamid Nawab]], Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering and Biomedical Engineering, [[Boston University]]; co-author of widely used textbook ''Signals and Systems'' (1997), published by [[Prentice Hall]] ([[Pearson Education|Pearson]]); researcher in [[signal processing]] and [[machine perception]] with application to auditory, speech, and neuromuscular systems\n*[[Agha Saeed]] \u2013 founder and Chairman of [[American Muslim Alliance]]; lecturer at [[California State University, East Bay]]{{cn|date=October 2017}}\n*[[Anwar Shaikh (economist)|Anwar Shaikh]] \u2013 Professor of Economics at the graduate faculty of [[The New School]] in New York City<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.newschool.edu/~AShaikh/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421170313/http://homepage.newschool.edu/~AShaikh/ |archivedate=April 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Sara Suleri]] \u2013 Professor of English at Yale University\n*[[Abdul Jamil Tajik]] \u2013 researcher in [[clinical medicine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?&link1=Browse&link2=Results&id=2918 |title=[ISI Highly Cited Researchers Version 1.5&#93; |publisher=Hcr3.isiknowledge.com |date=November 22, 2002 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Muhammad Suhail Zubairy]] \u2013 Professor in the Department of Physics and Astronomy; holder of the Munnerlyn-Heep Chair in Quantum Optics at the [[Texas A&M University]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://physics.tamu.edu/people/showpeople.php?name=M.%20Suhail%20Zubairy&userid=zubairy |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 28, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090928053740/http://physics.tamu.edu/people/showpeople.php?name=M.%20Suhail%20Zubairy&userid=zubairy |archive-date=September 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Activism and politics==\n[[File:Zalmay Khalilzad with George W. Bush in 2004.jpg|300px|thumb|Former UN ambassador [[Zalmay Khalilzad]] with President [[George W. Bush]] at the [[White House]]]]\n*[[Huma Abedin]] \u2013 aide to United States Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]]; served as traveling chief of staff during Clinton's campaign for the Democratic nomination in the 2008 presidential election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sepiamutiny.com/sepia/archives/004874.html |title=The first desi in the Oval Office? |publisher=Sepia Mutiny |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Saqib Ali]] \u2013 served as delegate to the [[Maryland House of Delegates]], elected in 2006, represented the 39th District<ref name=\"Hindustan\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/5967_1838839,001600060001.htm |title=Indo-Americans make a mark in US polls |work=Hindustan Times |location=India |date=November 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927195906/http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/5967_1838839,001600060001.htm |archivedate=September 27, 2007 |df=mdy-all }} Retrieved December 10, 2006</ref>\n* Tahir Ali \u2013 first Pakistani American elected as a National delegate-at-large (R) from [[Massachusetts]], 1992<ref>[http://www.amp.ghazali.net/html/tahir_ali-0.html Tahir Ali] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723134439/http://www.amp.ghazali.net/html/tahir_ali-0.html |date=July 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n*[[Arif Alikhan]] \u2013 former appointee to the Obama Administration where he served as Assistant Secretary for Policy Development at the United States [[Department of Homeland Security]]; former Deputy Mayor of Homeland Security and Public Safety for the City of Los Angeles; visiting Professor of Homeland Security and Counterterrorism at the [[National Defense University]]'s (NDU) College of International Security Affairs in Washington, DC\n*[[Nihad Awad]] \u2013 National Executive Director of the Council on American-Islamic Relations\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Carson]] \u2013 [[United States Congress|Congress]]man from [[Indiana]]<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN1164415020080312 \"Second Muslim elected to Congress\"] Reuters. 2008-03-11. Retrieved on 2009-06-16.</ref>\n*[[Shamila N. Chaudhary]] \u2013 [[US government]] policy adviser<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/s/p/120244.htm |title=Chaudhary, Shamila N |publisher=State.gov |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100228085656/http://www.state.gov/s/p/120244.htm |archive-date=February 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Robert D. Crane]] \u2013 former foreign policy advisor; author<ref>[http://www.islamonline.net/livedialogue/english/Guestcv.asp?hGuestID=gTlc0C IslamonLine.net<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102102349/http://www.islamonline.net/livedialogue/english/Guestcv.asp?hGuestID=gTlc0C |date=January 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n*[[Sada Cumber]] \u2013 first US envoy to the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Organisation of the Islamic Conference]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/101432.htm |accessdate=April 24, 2010 }}</ref>\n*[[Keith Ellison (politician)|Keith Ellison]] \u2013 first Muslim [[United States Congress|congress]]man from Minnesota<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/6127234.stm \"First Muslim congressman elected\"] BBC News. Retrieved on 2009-06-16.</ref>\n*[[George Bethune English]] (1787-1828) \u2013 American adventurer, diplomat, soldier, and convert to Islam.\n*[[Ibrahim Hooper]] \u2013 National Communications Director for the [[Council on American-Islamic Relations]] (CAIR)\n*[[Mansoor Ijaz]] \u2013 hedge fund manager and venture capitalist involved in [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations]] and peace efforts surrounding the [[Kashmir conflict]]\n*[[Arsalan Iftikhar]] \u2013 human rights lawyer, global media commentator, and author of the book ''Scapegoats: How Islamophobia Helps Our Enemies & Threatens Our Freedoms''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/12/islam-twitter_n_860726.html#s277449&title=Arsalan_Iftikhar_AKA |title=Islam On Twitter |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-19}}</ref>\n*[[Queen Noor of Jordan|Noor Al-Hussein]] \u2013 anti-[[nuclear weapons proliferation]] advocate and former [[Queen consort of Jordan]]\n*[[Hakim Jamal]] \u2013 civil rights activist; Member of the [[Nation of Islam]] but converted to traditional Islam after the assassination of his cousin Malcolm X.\n*[[Zalmay Khalilzad]] \u2013 former [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|US Ambassador to the United Nations]]; former [[United States Ambassador to Iraq|U.S. Ambassador to Iraq]] and [[United States Ambassador to Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4736394.stm | work=BBC News | title=Zalmay Khalilzad: US power broker | date=2007-01-08 | accessdate=2010-05-08}}</ref>\n*[[Yuri Kochiyama]] \u2013 [[Japanese American]] [[activist]] who converted to [[Sunni Islam]] from [[Protestantism]] in 1971{{sfn|Fujino|2005|p=206}}\n*[[Umar Lee]] \u2013 Activist and Writer\n*[[Edina Lekovic]] \u2013 Communications Director of the [[Muslim Public Affairs Council]]<ref>[http://frum.nationalreview.com/post/?q=YzBmOGRlNjJjMmJlZGEyNjJiNWFkZWMyY2E1Mjk1OTY= National Review Online] Retrieved on 2009-06-18.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206131018/http://frum.nationalreview.com/post/?q=YzBmOGRlNjJjMmJlZGEyNjJiNWFkZWMyY2E1Mjk1OTY%3D |date=December 6, 2006 }}</ref>\n*[[Gholam Mujtaba]]  \u2013  chair of the Pakistan Policy Institute, a think tank dedicated to improve the US-Pakistan relationship\n*[[Ilhan Omar]] \u2013 One of the first two Muslim women elected to Congress.<ref name=omar-tlaib>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hannahallam/rashida-tlaib-ilhan-omar-muslim-congress|title=Rashida Tlaib And Ilhan Omar Are The First Muslim Women Elected To Congress|publisher=BuzzFeed News|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Farah Pandith]] \u2013 Special Representative to Muslim Communities for the US Department of State; official advisor to President Obama on Muslim matters\n*[[Zainab Salbi]] \u2013 co-founder and president for [[Women for Women International]] \n*[[Betty Shabazz]] (also known as Betty X) \u2013 civil rights activist and educator; widow of Malcolm X<ref>[http://www.gale.cengage.com/free_resources/bhm/bio/shabazz_b.htm \"Betty Shabazz\"] Gale Ceneage Learning</ref>\n*[[Ilyasah Shabazz]] \u2013 social activist and daughter of Malcolm X\n*[[Malcolm Shabazz]] \u2013 activist and grandson of Malcolm X; [[Malcolm_Shabazz#Death|Murdered]] during a labor rights tour in [[Mexico]]\n*[[Malcolm X|el-Hajj Malik el-Shabazz]] (also known as Malcolm X) \u2013 human rights activist, civil rights activist, public speaker and [[Nation of Islam|Black Muslim]] minister;<ref>''The Last Speeches''. Bruce Perry, ed. New York: Pathfinder Press (1989). p. 261.</ref> Joined the Nation of Islam in 1952, before converting to Sunni Islam in 1964.\n*[[Azadeh Shahshahani]] \u2013 human rights attorney and past president of the [[National Lawyers Guild]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/05/31/from-tehran-to-atlanta-social-justice-lawyer-azadeh-shahshahanis-fight-for-human-rights/ |title=From Tehran to Atlanta: Social Justice Lawyer Azadeh Shahshahani's Fight for Human Rights |publisher=Counterpunch F|date=2016-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[Saghir \"Saggy\" Tahir]] \u2013 [[New Hampshire]] State